## Step 5 — Recommendations

Ranked by impact-per-effort.

### High-impact, low-effort

**1. Update the roadmap to reflect 1c.3 reality.** Add a "Phase 1c.3 — current" section parallel to the existing "Phase 1c.2 cleanup — current" section. List Slices A, B, C, D, E with one-line outcomes, link to each slice doc. List 1c.3-F retrospective as the next slice if that's the plan. Effort: 20 min. Closes the largest comprehension gap I hit.

**2. Add a roadmap-update step to the slice-shipping workflow.** Workflows.md already says "Add the slice to the phase's roadmap entry"; the discipline has lapsed for 1c.3. Either enforce it at slice close or move the canonical "what slices have shipped" list to be auto-derivable from frontmatter scanning `docs/process/phase-*-outcome.md` (the slice files themselves are reliable; the roadmap is the lossy summary). Effort: a convention update plus a stale-roadmap detector script (an hour).

**3. Add a pipeline-trace doc.** `docs/architecture/pipeline-trace.md` walking one upload from INSERT to result row with file:line citations. Bridges the `architecture/` (component-scoped) and the edge function code (line-scoped) layers. Effort: 1-2 hours. Closes Q7 synthesis cost permanently.

**4. Add a "current state" tag at the top of `repo-architecture-audit.md`.** Status banner: "Recommendations executed. See CHANGELOG for delivery; this doc is retained as historical record of the prompting-document for the cleanup." Effort: 5 min. Eliminates the "wait, is this done?" reading moment.

### Medium-impact, medium-effort

**5. Architecture overview at the system level.** `docs/architecture/system-overview.md` covering Brand HQ, Athlete Lab, Athlete Profile, Cloud Run, edge functions, Supabase, Lovable AI Gateway, and how they connect. The repo audit named this gap; it's not yet closed. Use the pipeline-trace doc (rec 3) as one of the cross-cutting examples. Effort: 2-3 hours.

**6. Phase 2 starter-pack doc.** When 1c.3 closes, before Phase 2a kickoff, write `docs/process/phase-2a-kickoff.md` listing required pre-reads. Pattern repeats for 2b and 2c. Effort: 30 min per kickoff.

**7. Cost-model reference doc.** `docs/reference/cost-model.md` enumerating per-analysis cost (Cloud Run, LLM tokens, storage), who pays, what scales. Even an unfinished doc would be useful — it would force F-SLICE-E-2 cold-start cost analysis to have a home. Effort: 1 hour for first pass.

**8. Lede for F-OPS-4.** Add a one-paragraph "what this finding is about" intro before the evolution log. The methodological lesson is genuinely portable; the slice-specific examples currently dominate the finding's surface area. Effort: 15 min.

### Lower-impact, optional

**9. Tier-source-of-truth resolution.** When 1c.3 closes, decide whether the canonical tier IDs are `youth | high-school | college | pro` (code) or `Youth | High School | College | Professional` (VISION) or "to be defined" (schema). Probably code wins because the form binds to it. Then update VISION's tier-language section and remove the schema's "no canonical set yet" caveat.

**10. R2 stub cleanup.** Seven stubs are now in the queue. As 1c.3 closes, run the `rg` sweep and remove any stubs without live references. The CHANGELOG already has the inventory.

### Possibly missing entirely (can't fully articulate)

**Test infrastructure narrative.** The repo audit explicitly rejected CI/CD (R1) and hosted observability (R2) for good reasons — the manual per-slice verification model is what catches real bugs. But there is no doc that captures the philosophy of testing in this repo. New contributors raised on CI culture will look for it and either propose adding CI (which has been considered and rejected) or assume the project is under-tested (which is the wrong frame). A short `docs/agents/testing-philosophy.md` explaining: per-slice manual verification is the test surface, verification scripts in `scripts/verification/` carry headers per Pass 6.3, the calibration audit rollup CSV is the regression dataset, and CI is deferred until cadence justifies it. ~30 min to write.

